## Why Asked
Interview context: Tests understanding of scalable test infrastructure design and architectural trade-offs in enterprise testing environments.

## Key Concepts
Core knowledge: WebDriver for single browser automation, Grid's hub-node topology for distributed testing, session management, resource allocation, parallel execution strategies.

## Architecture Deep Dive
Selenium Grid uses a centralized hub that manages test sessions and routes requests to distributed nodes. The hub acts as a load balancer and session manager, while nodes register their capabilities (browser types, versions, platforms) and execute actual browser sessions. Each node can handle multiple concurrent sessions based on available resources, typically 4-6 sessions per 8GB RAM.

## Large-Scale Use Cases
Netflix runs 50,000+ daily parallel tests using multi-region hub architecture to reduce latency and improve fault tolerance. E-commerce platforms leverage Grid for Black Friday readiness testing, simulating thousands of concurrent users across Chrome, Firefox, Safari, and mobile browsers. CI/CD pipelines integrate Grid for comprehensive cross-browser validation before deployments.

## Code Example
```java
// Grid configuration for large-scale testing
DesiredCapabilities caps = new DesiredCapabilities();
caps.setBrowserName("chrome");
caps.setPlatform(Platform.WINDOWS_10);
caps.setVersion("latest");

// Connect to load-balanced hub
URL hubUrl = new URL("https://grid.company.com:4444/wd/hub");
WebDriver driver = new RemoteWebDriver(hubUrl, caps);

// Configure session timeout and retry logic
driver.manage().timeouts().pageLoadTimeout(30, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
```

## Performance Optimization
Implement session pooling with pre-warmed browsers, set aggressive 300-second idle timeouts, and monitor memory usage (1.5GB per session). Use health checks every 30 seconds to detect zombie nodes, and configure auto-scaling based on queue depth. Always call driver.quit() instead of driver.close() to ensure proper cleanup and prevent memory leaks.
